✅ What are Server Components in Next.js / React?
Server Components are a modern React feature (used heavily in Next.js App Router) that let you render components on the server instead of the browser.
They run only on the server, send HTML + serialized data to the client, and do not ship JavaScript unless needed.
	In short: Server Components improve performance, security, and data access by moving work off the client.

🔹 Key Idea (Plain English)
	• Client Components → run in the browser
	• Server Components → run on the server
With Server Components:
	• No extra JS sent to browser
	• Faster page loads
	• Direct access to backend resources

🧱 Server Components in Next.js App Router
In Next.js App Router (app/):
✅ All components are Server Components by default

// app/page.js
export default function Page() {
  return <h1>Hello from Server Component</h1>;
}
This component:
	• Runs on the server
	• Is not included in the client JS bundle

🔹 What Server Components Can Do (Very Important)
✅ Fetch data directly from:
	• Databases
	• Internal APIs
	• File system
✅ Use sensitive data:
	• Secrets
	• Tokens
	• Environment variables
✅ Reduce JS bundle size
✅ Improve SEO and performance

✅ Example: Server Component with Data Fetching

// app/users/page.js
export default async function UsersPage() {
  const users = await fetch("https://api.example.com/users").then(r => r.json());
  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
✅ No getServerSideProps
✅ Runs fully on the server
✅ Clean and readable

🔹 What Server Components Cannot Do
❌ Use browser‑only APIs
	• window
	• document
	• localStorage
❌ Use React hooks like:
	• useState
	• useEffect
	• useContext
❌ Handle user interactions (clicks, input)
👉 For these, you need Client Components

🔹 Client Components vs Server Components
Client Component

"use client";
import { useState } from "react";
export default function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;
}
``
✅ Runs in the browser
✅ Used for interactivity

⚖️ Server vs Client Components (Quick Comparison)
Aspect	Server Component	Client Component
Runs on	Server	Browser
JS sent to browser	❌ No	✅ Yes
Data access	Direct (DB, APIs)	API only
Hooks	❌ No	✅ Yes
Interactivity	❌ No	✅ Yes
Performance	✅ Very high	Medium

🔄 Mixing Server and Client Components
✅ Server Components can import Client Components
❌ Client Components cannot import Server Components

// Server Component
import Counter from "./Counter";
export default function Page() {
  return <Counter />;
}
This creates a clean separation:
	• Server → data & layout
	• Client → interaction

🧠 Why Server Components Matter (Interview Gold)
✅ Smaller JS bundles
✅ Faster First Contentful Paint
✅ Better scalability
✅ Improved security
✅ Cleaner architecture

🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer
	Server Components are React components that run on the server and send rendered output to the client without shipping JavaScript. In Next.js App Router, components are Server Components by default. They allow direct data fetching, reduce bundle size, improve performance, and enhance security, while Client Components are used only where interactivity is needed.

✅ When to Use Server Components
✅ Data‑heavy pages
✅ SEO‑focused pages
✅ Layouts and static UI
✅ Secure backend access

✅ When NOT to Use Them
❌ Forms with client validation
❌ Click handlers, modals, animations
❌ Browser‑only logic

